article.description: Former Liberty star Becky Hammon scored 23 of her season-high 30 points in the second half to lead the San Antonio Silver Stars to an 82-76 victory at New York on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Former Liberty G Hammon burns ex-mates as Silver Stars take first in West
article.linkText: Hammon rips old team as Silver Stars nip Liberty
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Becky Hammon made herself right at home in Madison Square Garden.

The former Liberty star scored 23 of her season-high 30 points in the second half to lead the San Antonio Silver Stars to an 82-76 victory at New York on Tuesday night.

"I got more games here than any other building," said Hammon, who spent her first eight seasons with the Liberty before being traded to San Antonio on draft day last year.

Sophia Young had 15 points and Erin Buescher added 13 for San Antonio (22-10), which won for the fifth time in six games and took over sole possession of first place in the Western Conference -- one game ahead of Seattle, which lost at Sacramento.

Hammon had 13 points in the third quarter and then eight points on free throws in the final 1:12 to help the Silver Stars hold on and improve to 13-0 against the Eastern Conference.

"They were in a tough situation because they had to foul," said Hammon, shooting 94 percent from the line the last three seasons said. "They had to foul me. That's my job as a point guard. I'm a pretty good free-throw shooter."

Hammon finished 8-for-14 from the field, including 4-for-8 on 3s, and 10-for-10 from the free-throw line.

Shameka Christon and Jessica Davenport scored 15 points each for third-place New York (18-13), which is 1 1/2 games behind Connecticut and Detroit and in the East. Essence Carson and Erlana Larkins added 13 points each.

Two more former Liberty stars -- Vickie Johnson, New York's career leader in several categories including points and games played, and Ann Wauters -- also came up big on their former court. Wauters had 11 points and 10 rebounds, and Johnson also scored 11.

"It is always something special to play here in New York," Wauters said. "It was a tough win on the road. ... Our defense was better in the second half. ... We really had to focus on that in the second half, and that was the difference in the game."

Christon returned after missing three games with a strained right hamstring, but New York was without Janel McCarville (back spasms) and Tiffany Jackson (stress fracture).

"I knew this game was going to be kind of 'iffy," Christon said. "We are now coming back and getting in the flow of things. The main thing is we have clinched a playoff spot, so there is really no pressure."

Carson's 3-pointer gave the Liberty their last lead, 47-44 with 5:49 left in the third quarter.

San Antonio then went on a 12-2 run, taking the lead for good on Johnson's layup with 5:09 to go in the period. Hammon's 3 pushed the lead to 56-49 with about 2 1/2 minutes left.

"Becky is a terrific player," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "When we traded her, we understood what we were trading. She's in a situation now where she's playing with great players. ... You put emphasis on her and then the other ones kill you. You try to take the others away and she kills you. They have a good balance."

Davenport hit two free throws to pull New York to 62-59 with 7:08 left in the fourth quarter, but that was as close as the Liberty got.

Erin Buescher hit two free throws for the Silver Stars, Wauters blocked Erin Thorn's layup and Johnson made a fastbreak layup at the other end to push San Antonio's lead to seven with 5 1/2 minutes left.

Neither team led by more than five points in the first half, which ended tied at 35-35.
